The '''BMW R1200R''' is a [[Types of motorcycles#Standard|standard]] motorcycle introduced in 2006 by [[BMW Motorrad]].<ref name="telegraph">{{cite web | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/motorbikes/2742280/Tactile-victory.html | title= Tactile Victory | first= Kevin | last= Ash |authorlink=Kevin Ash | date= 15 July 2006 | accessdate= 26 August 2009 | publisher= [[The Daily Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref> It replaces the [[BMW R1150R|R1150R]], compared with which it has a {{cvt|55|lb}} weight saving and 28% increase in power.<ref name="telegraph" />

[[File:2015 bmw r1200r.jpg|left|thumb|2015 BMW R1200R]]
For model year 2015, a completely new R1200R with the same {{cvt|125|hp}} liquid/air-cooled engine as the 2014/2015 [[BMW R1200RT|R1200RT]], but weighing 100 pounds less, was introduced.<ref name="engine">{{cite web |url=http://www.bmwmotorcycles.com/us/en/index.html?gclid=CIaq7vPY3tQCFVi4wAodd-QKqg//|title=R 1200 R | publisher=[[BMW]]|accessdate=June 27, 2017|year= 2017 }}</ref>{{better source|date=July 2019|reason=see [[WP:ABOUTSELF]] }}

For the 2019 Model Year, the R1200R was succeeded by the R1250R. The R1250R features a newer dual cam profile engine and has a TFT display.

