The '''Triumph Thunderbird''' is [[Triumph Motorcycles Ltd|Triumph]] [[motorcycle]] made in [[Hinckley]], England, and sold since June 2009.<ref name=torygraph>{{cite news | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/motorbikes/5357085/Triumph-Thunderbird-review.html | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090524200708/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/motorbikes/5357085/Triumph-Thunderbird-review.html | url-status= dead | archive-date= 24 May 2009 | title= Triumph Thunderbird review | last= Ash | first= Kevin |authorlink=Kevin Ash | newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph]] | date= 22 May 2009 | accessdate= 23 May 2009}}</ref>  
The name "Thunderbird" is revived from a previous Triumph three-cylinder 885&nbsp;cc bike. The name was previously applied to a single carburettor version of the 650cc twin Bonneville produced in the mid-1960s for police work. The final iteration was the Thunderbird Sport, last made in 2004.

==Design==
[[File:2011Sept 021.jpg|thumb|left|2011 Triumph Thunderbird Storm]]
The Thunderbird is a [[Cruiser (motorcycle)|cruiser]] with a large 200/50 R17 rear tyre.  [[Motorcycle design|Design]] was by [[Tim Prentice (designer)|Tim Prentice]] in [[California]].<ref name=torygraph/><ref>{{citation|title=2-wheel lowdown|last=Winfield|first=Barry|journal=[[Autoweek]]|page=40|volume=59|number=20|date=October 2009|id={{ProQuest|218931195}}}}</ref> The [[DOHC]] eight-valve [[Straight-twin engine|parallel-twin engine]] has two [[balance shaft]]s and a [[Straight-twin engine#270°|270° crank]], which imitates the sound and feel of a [[V-twin engine|V-twin]].  The {{convert|1597|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} engine was originally intended to be [[modular design|modular]], namely "two-thirds of" a [[Triumph Rocket III]] engine; but after four years of development, the only parts in common are the valves.  Power output is {{convert|85|bhp|kW PS|abbr=on}} and torque is {{convert|108|lb.ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=torygraph/> 
The engine has two spark plugs per cylinder, which gives better combustion, resulting in lower fuel consumption, cleaner exhaust emissions, and more power. Brakes are double front discs with four-piston callipers, with a single rear disc also with two-piston callipers (ABS as option).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twowheelsblog.com/post/477/2009-triumph-thunderbird-1600|title=Thunderbird 1600|accessdate=4 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080814212847/http://www.twowheelsblog.com/post/477/2009-triumph-thunderbird-1600|archivedate=14 August 2008}}</ref> Final drive is via a [[Gilmer belt|belt drive]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fasterandfaster.net/2008/07/first-pics-2009-triumph-thunderbird.html|title=First pics: 2009 Triumph Thunderbird 1600|accessdate=6 September 2008}}</ref>

In 2011, the Thunderbird Storm variant model was released featuring the previously-optional {{convert|1699|cc|cuin|abbr=on}} engine fitted as standard, twin headlamps and with a number of black, rather than chrome parts<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.motorcycle.com/manufacturer/triumph/2011-triumph-thunderbird-storm-review-90408.html | first= Troy | last= Siahaan| date= 8 February 2011 | publisher= Motorcycle.com | title= 2011 Triumph Thunderbird Storm Review | accessdate= 17 June 2011}}</ref>
{{clear left}}

==Reception==

A road test of the Thunderbird by ''[[Motorcycle News]]'' in May 2009,<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.motorcyclenews.com/MCN/News/newsresults/First-rides--tests/2009/May/may1409-triumph-thunderbird-first-ride/ | publisher= [[Motorcycle News]] | title=  First ride: Triumph Thunderbird | date= 14 May 2009 | accessdate= 23 May 2009}}</ref>
found that the motorcycle performed well, and handling and braking were significantly superior to comparable American or Japanese cruiser models.
In 2009 and 2010, US motorcycle magazine ''[[Cycle World]]'' awarded the Thunderbird "Best Cruiser" in its annual "Ten Best Bikes" feature.<ref>{{cite magazine | title= 2010 Ten Best Bikes Best Cruiser: Triumph Thunderbird 1600 | url= http://www.cycleworld.com/motorcycle_roadtest/ten_best_bikes_2010/best_cruiser_triumph_thunderbird_1600 | magazine= Cycle World |date=July 2010 | issn= 0011-4286}}</ref>

